\f0\fs28 \cf7  You are almost there:\
\
Look for the Vbe (on) for a transistor of choice. For a Darlington, say 2v\
\
Subtract the from the control voltage and you get 10v\
\
Take the transistor controlled current (in this case 1A)\
\
Divide by the gain of the transistor to get the base current needed - That gain is hfe\
\
Let's say it is 2000.\
\
The base current needed is 1/2000 = 0.5mA\
\
That base current has to flow through the resistor as the absolute minimum.\
\
So the resistor has 10v across it and say 1mA through it - so its resistance will be 10k\
\
You also need the Vce(on) (aka Vce sat) at 1A collector current. Let's say that it is 1v\
\
So there is 1v across the transistor with 1A flowing through it. So it will dissipate 1W.\
\
Now you need to calculate the heatsink needed for the transistor, to prevent it overheating.\
\
Let's say that you don't want it going over 70 C and ambient temperature is 20C. So the maximum temperature rise is going to be 50C\
\
Let's say that the transistor has a thermal resistance of 62.5 degrees/Watt to ambient - it will get too hot. So we need to add a heat sink.\
\
It's thermal resistance to case is say 2 degrees C per watt. So with 1W the heatsink will be 2 degrees colder than the chip. So the maximum temperature rise of the heatsink is going to be 48C per watt.\
\
You fit a heatsink with a rating that is better than 48C per watt..\
\
